[4] Cholera - Kenya (Murang'a County)
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2018 12:00 pm EAT
Source: The Star [edited]
https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/2018/02/27/46-admitted-after-cholera-outbreak-in-gatanga-muranga_c1721590


Two people have died and more than 40 been admitted [to hospital] after a suspected cholera outbreak in Nyaga village, Gatanga, Murang'a county. 35 [have been] admitted to Thika level 5 hospital while 11 are being treated at Kiunyu dispensary following the outbreak on Sun 25 Feb 2018.

According to Health CEC [county executive in-charge] Joseph Mbai, 8 out of the 225 residents screened have been confirmed to carry the cholera strains. Mbai has also directed all eateries to close down as the county government fights to contain the outbreak. "We are still appealing to all residents of this village to come out for screening," Mbai said, noting that those who are too weak to reach the dispensary are being ferried using ambulances.

A team of water experts from the Ministry of Water and Irrigation have, however, collected samples from Gathwariga river for testing. Residents had expressed fears that the disease had emanated from the river after a construction company that is tarmacking the Kiunyu Nyaga road destroyed water pipes, cutting off their tap water.

The health officials have collected samples from other water sources such as boreholes to establish where the disease spread from.

[byline: Alice Waithera]

